        <p>Cortisol reduction, anxiety relief, improved sleep quality, testosterone support, stress resilience. Works via HPA axis modulation and GABAergic enhancement. Effects in 2-4 weeks.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="vs-item vs-best">
        <span class="vs-item-label">Lion's Mane</span>
        <h3>The Cognitive Enhancer</h3>
        <div class="vs-dose">1,000-3,000mg/day (Fruiting Body)</div>
        <p>NGF stimulation, memory improvement, focus enhancement, neuroprotection. Works via hericenone/erinacine-mediated neurotrophin synthesis. Effects in 2-8 weeks.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- DETAILED COMPARISON TABLE -->
    <h2 id="detailed-comparison">Detailed Factor-by-Factor Analysis</h2>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Mechanism of Action</strong>
        <p><strong>Ashwagandha:</strong> Withanolides modulate the HPA axis, directly reducing cortisol production. Also enhances GABA receptor activity for calming effects. <strong>Lion's Mane:</strong> Hericenones and erinacines cross the blood-brain barrier to stimulate NGF synthesis, promoting neuron growth and synaptic plasticity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Clinical Evidence Strength</strong>
        <p><strong>Ashwagandha:</strong> Over 24 clinical trials using KSM-66 alone, plus hundreds of studies on the raw herb. Multiple systematic reviews and meta-analyses published. <strong>Lion's Mane:</strong> Fewer human trials (approximately 10-15) but strong mechanistic evidence from in vitro and animal studies. The 2009 Mori et al. RCT is the landmark human study.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Best For: Stress & Anxiety</strong>
        <p><strong>Winner: Ashwagandha.</strong> A 2019 meta-analysis of 5 RCTs confirmed significant anxiety reduction. Cortisol levels decrease by 23-30% in clinical studies. Lion's mane has some preliminary evidence for mood improvement but is not primarily an anxiolytic.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Best For: Focus & Memory</strong>
        <p><strong>Winner: Lion's Mane.</strong> Direct NGF stimulation supports neuroplasticity and memory formation. The 2009 double-blind RCT showed significant cognitive improvement in older adults after 16 weeks. Ashwagandha can improve focus indirectly by reducing stress-related cognitive interference.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Best For: Sleep</strong>
        <p><strong>Winner: Ashwagandha.</strong> A 2020 systematic review of 5 RCTs found significant sleep quality improvement (SMD 0.68). Contains triethylene glycol that promotes non-REM sleep. Lion's mane has no documented sleep-promoting effects and is better suited for daytime use.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Best For: Neuroprotection</strong>
        <p><strong>Winner: Lion's Mane.</strong> NGF stimulation directly supports neuron survival and repair. Research suggests potential applications in age-related cognitive decline and neurodegenerative conditions. Ashwagandha has some neuroprotective properties through oxidative stress reduction, but lacks the direct neurotrophic mechanism.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2019 meta-analysis in the <em>Journal of Alternative and Complementary Medicine</em> found that ashwagandha supplementation produced <strong>significant reductions in anxiety scores</strong> across all 5 randomized controlled trials analyzed. Separately, the landmark 2009 Mori et al. trial found that <strong>3g/day of lion's mane for 16 weeks significantly improved cognitive function</strong> in adults aged 50-80 — benefits that reversed after supplementation stopped.</p>
      <cite>J. Alt. Comp. Med., 2019 (ashwagandha) / Phytotherapy Research, 2009 (lion's mane)</cite>
    </div>

    <!-- WHEN TO USE EACH -->
    <h2 id="when-to-use">When to Use Ashwagandha vs Lion's Mane</h2>

    <h3>Choose Ashwagandha If You...</h3>
