    <!-- DOSAGE COMPARISON -->
    <h2 id="dosage">Dosage Comparison</h2>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Ashwagandha Dosage</strong>
        <p><strong>KSM-66:</strong> 300-600mg per day, standardized to 5% withanolides. Most clinical trials use 600mg. <strong>Sensoril:</strong> 125-250mg per day, standardized to 10% withanolides. Higher concentration means lower required dose. Take with food to improve absorption and reduce GI discomfort.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Lion's Mane Dosage</strong>
        <p><strong>Fruiting body extract:</strong> 1,000-3,000mg per day. The most commonly cited effective dose is 1,000mg of a standardized extract. Look for products specifying fruiting body source with beta-glucan content above 20%. Take with or without food — bioavailability is not significantly affected by meal timing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Ashwagandha Forms</strong>
        <p>KSM-66 (root only, most versatile), Sensoril (root + leaf, highest withanolide concentration), generic powder (unstandardized, less reliable). Gummies typically deliver 300-600mg per serving. Always verify the extract type on the supplement facts panel.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Lion's Mane Forms</strong>
        <p>Fruiting body extract (highest hericenone content, preferred), mycelium-on-grain (lower bioactive concentration, higher starch filler), dual extract (hot water + alcohol, captures full spectrum). Gummies typically deliver 500-1,000mg per serving. Verify the mushroom source.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SAFETY COMPARISON -->
    <h2 id="safety">Safety and Side Effects Comparison</h2>

    <p>Both ashwagandha and lion's mane have excellent safety profiles in clinical research. However, they have different contraindication profiles that are important to understand.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Ashwagandha Cautions</strong>
        <p>May increase thyroid hormone production — avoid with hyperthyroidism. May lower blood sugar — monitor if taking diabetes medications. May increase testosterone — not suitable during pregnancy. Avoid with autoimmune conditions (may stimulate immune activity). May interact with sedatives, blood pressure medications, and immunosuppressants.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Lion's Mane Cautions</strong>
        <p>Avoid if you have mushroom allergies. May have mild anticoagulant properties — consult physician if taking blood thinners. May affect blood sugar regulation — monitor if on diabetes medications. Very few reported adverse effects in clinical trials. Generally considered one of the safest nootropic supplements available.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

