    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take ashwagandha and lion's mane together?</summary>
      <p>Yes. They work through entirely different mechanisms — ashwagandha modulates cortisol via the HPA axis while lion's mane stimulates NGF via hericenones and erinacines. A common protocol is lion's mane in the morning for daytime focus and ashwagandha in the evening for stress recovery and sleep. No adverse interactions have been reported in published literature.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Which is better for anxiety: ashwagandha or lion's mane?</summary>
      <p>Ashwagandha has stronger clinical evidence for anxiety. A 2019 meta-analysis of 5 RCTs found significant anxiety reduction on the Hamilton Anxiety Rating Scale. The mechanism involves direct cortisol reduction and GABAergic modulation. Lion's mane has preliminary evidence for mood improvement but is primarily a cognitive enhancer, not an anxiolytic.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Which is better for focus and memory?</summary>
